<div id="review_3585098031" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3585098031" />
    <a title="La Coccinelle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3972045-la-coccinelle"><img alt="La Coccinelle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1410480686p2/3972045.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3585098031?book_show_action=true">Oct 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="La Coccinelle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="La Coccinelle" href="/user/show/3972045-la-coccinelle">La Coccinelle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780399252969" href="/book/show/6496033-the-mitten">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3972045-la-coccinelle?shelf=children">children</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3585098031" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11335250506952518957">I can&apos;t recall ever reading <i>The Mitten</i> before. I assumed it was a Christmas story, but it&apos;s not; it&apos;s simply a winter story, set in snowy Ukraine.<br/><br/>A boy named Nicki wants a pair of snow-white mittens. His grandmother is skeptical, thinking he&apos;ll lose them in the snow where he won&apos;t be able to find them. But he insists, and is gifted with a pair of white mittens. Of course, he promptly loses one, and it becomes a source of comfort for a number of woodland animals, each of them squeezing into the m</span>
  <span id="freeText11335250506952518957" style="display:none">I can't recall ever reading <i>The Mitten</i> before. I assumed it was a Christmas story, but it's not; it's simply a winter story, set in snowy Ukraine.<br><br>A boy named Nicki wants a pair of snow-white mittens. His grandmother is skeptical, thinking he'll lose them in the snow where he won't be able to find them. But he insists, and is gifted with a pair of white mittens. Of course, he promptly loses one, and it becomes a source of comfort for a number of woodland animals, each of them squeezing into the magical mitten until an unexpected sneeze propels the story to its conclusion.<br><br>Jan Brett's artwork is always interesting, and it's lovely here, full of incredible detail. I enjoyed looking at the little side panels, which would give a hint about which animal was going to show up next to claim their space inside the mitten.<br><br>Overall, I enjoyed this one. It's easy to see why it's a classic. I read the 20th-anniversary edition, but the book is over 30 years old now. And it'll probably be enjoyed by readers for many more years to come.<br><br><b>Quotable moment:</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1602095362i/30205637._SX540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></span>
  <a data-text-id="11335250506952518957" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


